\par \pard \qc \li1200\ri1200 \sb0 \fi0 ABIGAIL NOEL FISHER, Petitioner, v. UNIVERSITY OF TEXAS AT AUSTIN, et al., Respondents.
\par \pard 
\par \pard \qc \li1200\ri1200 \sb0 \fi0 No. \cf17 \b \i0 \ul0 11-345\cf \b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \qc \li1200\ri1200 \sb0 \fi0 SUPREME COURT OF THE UNITED STATES
\par \pard 
\par \pard \qc \li1200\ri1200 \sb0 \fi0 2011 U.S. Briefs 345; 2012 U.S. S. Ct. Briefs LEXIS 3219
\par \pard 
\par \pard \qc \li1200\ri1200 \sb0 \fi0 August 13, 2012
\par \pard 
\par \pard \qc \li1200\ri1200 \sb0 \fi0 On Writ of Certiorari to the United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit.
\par \pard 
\par \pard \qc \li1200\ri1200 \sb0 \fi0 Amicus Brief
\par \pard 
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 COUNSEL: \b0 \i0 \ul0  \b \i0 \ul0 [**1]\b0 \i0 \ul0   JONATHAN M. COHEN, Counsel of Record, MARK A. PACKMAN, ADRIAN C. AZER, IVAN SNYDER, JENNA A. HUDSON, GILBERT LLP, Washington, DC, Counsel for National Bar Association. JOHN PAGE, DEMETRIS CHEATHAM, NATIONAL BAR ASSOCIATION, Washington, DC, BENNY AGOSTO, JR., PETER M. REYES, JR., HISPANIC NATIONAL BAR ASSOCIATION, Washington, DC, WENDY SHIBA, TINA MATSUOKA, NATIONAL ASIAN PACIFIC, AMERICAN BAR ASSOCIATION, Washington, DC, PATTY FERGUSON-BOHNEE, ROBERT O. SAUNOOKE, NATIONAL NATIVE, AMERICAN BAR ASSOCIATION, Oklahoma City, OK.  \b \i0 \ul0 [*i]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard 
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 INTERESTS: \b0 \i0 \ul0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*1]\b0 \i0 \ul0   \b \i0 \ul0 STATEMENT OF INTEREST OF \b \i \ul0 AMICI\b \i0 \ul0  CURIAE\b0 \i0 \ul0  n1
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n1 In accordance with Supreme Court Rule 37.6, \b0 \i \ul0 Amici Curiae\b0 \i0 \ul0  note that the position they take in this brief has not been approved or financed by Petitioners, Respondents, or their counsel. Neither Petitioners, Respondents, nor their counsel had any role in authoring, nor made any monetary contribution to fund the preparation or submission of, this brief. Pursuant to Supreme Court Rule 37.3, \b0 \i \ul0 Amici Curiae\b0 \i0 \ul0  state that all parties have consented to the filing of this brief; blanket letters of consent have been filed with the Clerk of the Court.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 This brief is filed on behalf of the National Bar Association, the Hispanic National Bar Association, the National Asian Pacific American Bar Association, and the National Native American Bar Association (collectively, "\b0 \i \ul0 Amici\b0 \i0 \ul0 "). \b0 \i \ul0 Amici\b0 \i0 \ul0  are bar associations whose members are predominantly minorities. \b0 \i \ul0 Amici\b0 \i0 \ul0  are partners in the Coalition of Bar Associations of Color, which was established in 1992. Members of the coalition meet annually to discuss issues of mutual concern and to advocate in support of shared interests with the executive branch and with elected officials.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The National Bar Association is the largest and oldest association of predominantly African-American attorneys and judges in the United States. The National Bar Association was founded in 1925 when there were only 1,000 African-American attorneys in the entire country and when other national bar associations, such as the American Bar Association ("ABA"), did not admit African-American attorneys. Throughout its history, the National Bar Association consistently has advocated on behalf of African Americans and other minority populations regarding  \b \i0 \ul0 [*2]\b0 \i0 \ul0   issues affecting the legal profession. The National Bar Association represents approximately 44,000 lawyers, judges, law professors, and law students, and it has over eighty affiliate chapters throughout the world.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The Hispanic National Bar Association is a nonprofit, nonpartisan, national professional association that represents the interests of over 100,000 attorneys, judges, law professors, legal assistants, and law students of Hispanic descent in the United States, Puerto Rico, and U.S. Virgin Islands. The Hispanic National Bar Association has thirty-eight affiliated bars in various states across the country. The Hispanic National Bar Association's continuing mission is to improve the study, practice, and administration of justice for all Americans by ensuring the meaningful participation of Hispanics in the legal profession.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The National Asian Pacific American Bar Association is the national association of Asian Pacific-American attorneys, judges, law professors, and law students, representing the interests of more than sixty state and local Asian Pacific-American bar associations and over 40,000 attorneys who work in solo practices, large firms, corporations, legal services organizations, nonprofit organizations, law schools, and government agencies. Since its inception in 1988, the National Asian Pacific American Bar Association has served as the national voice for Asian Pacific Americans in the legal profession and has promoted justice, equity, and opportunity for Asian Pacific Americans. The National Asian Pacific American Bar Association believes that there is a compelling  \b \i0 \ul0 [*3]\b0 \i0 \ul0   governmental interest in achieving diversity in higher education and supports upholding the use of race-conscious admissions programs in education. The National Asian Pacific American Bar Association opposes the use of Asian Pacific Americans as a wedge group in debates about affirmative action. n2
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n2 The National Asian Pacific American Bar Association joins this brief filed by its partners in the Coalition of Bar Associations of Color instead of a brief filed by its longtime partner, the Asian American Center for Advancing Justice ("AAJC"). Both the Coalition of Bar Associations of Color and AAJC have a longstanding commitment to serving the needs of Asian Pacific Americans and all communities of color, and the National Asian Pacific American Bar Association supports both briefs.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The National Native American Bar Association is the oldest and largest association of predominantly Native-American attorneys in the United States. n3 The National Native American Bar Association was founded in 1973 when the first group of Native-American attorneys was entering the legal profession. The National Native American Bar Association's core mission since its inception has been to promote the development of Native-American attorneys. Native Americans comprise one of the smallest groups of attorneys of color in the nation, totaling approximately 2,500. The National Native American Bar Association is committed to increasing the number of Native-American students who attend college and continue their education to attend law school. The National Native American Bar Association and its chapters are involved in pipeline initiatives to promote the  \b \i0 \ul0 [*4]\b0 \i0 \ul0   recruitment and retention of Native-American law students and law faculty. And an initiative of the National Native American Bar Association is to increase the appointment of Native Americans to the state and federal judiciaries; there are currently no Native-American Article III judges.
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n3 Native American includes American Indian, Alaska Native, and Native Hawaiian.
\par \fs20 \b0 \i \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Amici\b0 \i0 \ul0  have a deep interest in this case because the legal profession, which has had a long history of discrimination against racial minorities, is strengthened by racial and ethnic diversity. Diversity benefits all sectors of the legal profession, including both minority and non-minority members of the judiciary, lawyers, and clients. Diversity has these benefits because a diverse legal profession is better able to create and test new and innovative legal principles and ideas. For both minority and non-minority lawyers and judges, a diverse legal profession creates heightened sensitivity to the particular legal problems that minorities confront and the contexts for those legal challenges. A diverse legal profession also broadens the availability and effectiveness of legal representation, including by facilitating the provision of legal services to historically underserved communities.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Race-conscious college admissions programs enhance educational opportunities for minorities, thus creating a pipeline for greater minority participation in law schools and then through all levels of the legal system. Consequently, race-conscious college admissions programs are integral to achieving a critical mass of minorities in law schools and promoting diversity throughout the legal profession,  \b \i0 \ul0 [*5]\b0 \i0 \ul0   which is a compelling governmental interest. n4 Accordingly, the University of Texas's program should be upheld.
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n4 \b0 \i \ul0 Grutter v. Bollinger,\b0 \i0 \ul0  539 U.S. 306 (2003).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 TITLE: \b0 \i0 \ul0 \b \i0 \ul0 BRIEF OF AMICI CURIAE COALITION OF BAR ASSOCIATIONS OF COLOR (NATIONAL BAR ASSOCIATION, HISPANIC NATIONAL BAR ASSOCIATION, NATIONAL ASIAN PACIFIC AMERICAN BAR ASSOCIATION, AND NATIONAL NATIVE AMERICAN BAR ASSOCIATION) IN SUPPORT OF RESPONDENTS\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*6]\b0 \i0 \ul0   \b \i0 \ul0 SUMMARY OF ARGUMENT\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 This Court has long held that there is a compelling governmental interest in achieving and maintaining diversity in our Nation's educational system, and accordingly it has upheld race-conscious admissions programs directed at obtaining a "critical mass" of minority students. n5 This Court has recognized that diversity in the educational system not only has significant benefits for both minority and \b \i0 \ul0 [**11]\b0 \i0 \ul0   non-minority students' educational experiences but also creates a necessary pipeline for diversity in the Nation's professional ranks.
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n5 \b0 \i \ul0 Regents of the University of California v. Bakke,\b0 \i0 \ul0  438 U.S. 265, 269 (1978) (opinion of Powell, J.); \b0 \i \ul0 Grutter,\b0 \i0 \ul0  539 U.S. at 343.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In \b0 \i \ul0 Regents of the University of California v. Bakke,\b0 \i0 \ul0  for example, this Court's plurality opinion stated that "[t]he Nation's future depends upon leaders trained through wide exposure to that robust exchange of ideas which discovers truth 'out of a multitude of tongues, [rather] than through any kind of authoritative selection.'" n6 More recently, in \b0 \i \ul0 Grutter v. Bollinger,\b0 \i0 \ul0  this Court noted that "[e]ffective participation by members of all racial and ethnic groups in the civic life of our Nation is essential if the dream of one Nation, indivisible, is to be realized." n7
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n6 438 U.S. at 312 (opinion of Powell, J.) (quoting \b0 \i \ul0 United States v. Associated Press,\b0 \i0 \ul0  52 F. Supp. 362, 372 (S.D.N.Y. 1943)).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n7 539 U.S. at 332.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 There is no profession that benefits from diversity and civic engagement more than the legal  \b \i0 \ul0 [*7]\b0 \i0 \ul0    \b \i0 \ul0 [**12]\b0 \i0 \ul0   profession because "law schools represent the training ground for a large number of the Nation's leaders," and "legal learning and practice . . . cannot be effective in isolation from the individuals and institutions with which the law interacts." n8 Since the Court decided \b0 \i \ul0 Bakke\b0 \i0 \ul0  and \b0 \i \ul0 Grutter,\b0 \i0 \ul0  the profession has made great strides to diversify legal institutions, including private law firms and the judiciary.
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n8 \b0 \i \ul0 Id.\b0 \i0 \ul0  (citing \b0 \i \ul0 Sweatt v. Painter,\b0 \i0 \ul0  339 U.S. 629, 634 (1950)); \b0 \i \ul0 Sweatt,\b0 \i0 \ul0  339 U.S. at 634.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Progress, though, should not be confused with success. Racial minorities continue to be woefully underrepresented in virtually all segments of the legal profession, with certain racial minorities continuing to have almost no representation. For example, while African Americans equal more than 12% percent of the population, only 1.71% percent of law firm partners are African American. n9 Similarly, Hispanic Americans represent approximately 16% of the population, but only 1.92% of law firm partners, n10 and Asian Pacific Americans account for 4.76% of population, but only 2.36% of law firm partners. n11 Moreover, although Native Americans make \b \i0 \ul0 [**13]\b0 \i0 \ul0   up nearly 1% of the population, nationwide, there are too few Native-  \b \i0 \ul0 [*8]\b0 \i0 \ul0   American partners for the National Association of Law Placement ("NALP") to have included them in its study of minority legal employment. n12
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n9 \b0 \i \ul0 ACS Demographic and Housing Estimates,\b0 \i0 \ul0  American Community Survey 1 Year Estimates, US Census Bureau (2010), http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_10_1YR_DP05&prodType=table ("2010 Population"); \b0 \i \ul0 NALP Bulletin, Women and Minorities in Law Firms -- By Race and Ethnicity\b0 \i0 \ul0  (Jan. 2012), \b0 \i \ul0 available at\b0 \i0 \ul0  http://www.nalp.org/women_minorities_jan2012.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n10 2010 Population, \b0 \i \ul0 supra; NALP Bulletin, supra,\b0 \i0 \ul0  at 1.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n11 2010 Population, \b0 \i \ul0 supra; NALP Bulletin, supra,\b0 \i0 \ul0  at Table 2.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n12 2010 Population, \b0 \i \ul0 supra; NALP Bulletin, supra,\b0 \i0 \ul0  at 1.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 There is a similar lack of diversity in the judiciary. For example, in 2009, only 12.8% of judges sitting on state supreme courts nationwide were minorities. n13 And these statistics are even more dire when viewed at the individual state level. For example, in New Mexico, where minorities account for 57% of the population, minorities made up only \b \i0 \ul0 [**14]\b0 \i0 \ul0   15% and 18% of intermediate and trial court judges, respectively. n14
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n13 Gregory L. Acquaviva & John D. Castiglione, \b0 \i \ul0 Judicial Diversity on State Supreme Courts\b0 \i0 \ul0  39 Seton Hall L. Rev. 1203, 1215 (2009).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n14 Ciara Torres-Spelliscy et al., \b0 \i \ul0 Improving Judicial Diversity,\b0 \i0 \ul0  Brennan Center for Justice 1, 49 (2010), \b0 \i \ul0 available at\b0 \i0 \ul0  http://brennan.3cdn.net/31e6c0fa3c2e920910_ppm6ibehe.pdf.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Because of the continuing need to foster diversity in the legal profession, programs that enhance the opportunities for members of racial minorities in higher education -- like the one at the University of Texas -- are necessary. Indeed, if such programs were abolished, the impact on diversity in higher education would be significant. When race-conscious admissions programs were abolished in California, for instance, the population of racial minorities suffered as their admission into colleges and universities plummeted. In turn, the number of racial minorities entering into post-graduate education was disproportionately low,  \b \i0 \ul0 [*9]\b0 \i0 \ul0   with fewer racial minorities ultimately entering the legal profession.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 California's experience indicates that, if this Court were to \b \i0 \ul0 [**15]\b0 \i0 \ul0   overturn the University of Texas's race-conscious admissions program (and other similar programs), there likely would be a significant drop in the number of racial minorities admitted into colleges and universities, ultimately and necessarily reducing the number of racial minorities who enter law school and the legal profession. \b0 \i \ul0 Amici\b0 \i0 \ul0  thus support the constitutionality of the University of Texas's race-conscious admissions program, which furthers the compelling governmental interest in diversity both in education and in the legal profession.
\par \pard 
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 ARGUMENT\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 I. A COMPELLING GOVERNMENTAL INTEREST EXISTS IN CREATING AND MAINTAINING DIVERSITY IN THE LEGAL PROFESSION\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Lawyers play a central role in our government and the administration of our judicial system. Because of the pervasive nature of the legal system and its impact on the Nation's citizenry and history, this Court has recognized that it is important to ensure the inclusion and success of minority attorneys in every facet of the legal profession. n15
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n15 \b0 \i \ul0 See e.g., \b0 \i0 \ul0 \b0 \i \ul0 Grutter,\b0 \i0 \ul0  539 U.S. at 332.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [**16]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360  \b \i0 \ul0 [*10]\b0 \i0 \ul0   The Court's recognition of the importance of diversity in the legal profession is well supported by academic studies. n16 Scholars have identified at least four distinct benefits of creating diversity in the legal profession.
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n16 \b0 \i \ul0 See, e.g.,\b0 \i0 \ul0  David B. Rottman & Alan J. Tomkins, \b0 \i \ul0 Public Trust and Confidence in the Courts: What Public Opinion Surveys Mean to Judges,\b0 \i0 \ul0  Court Review, Fall 1999, at 24, 26; \b0 \i \ul0 see also\b0 \i0 \ul0  Michelle J. Anderson, \b0 \i \ul0 Legal Education Reform, Diversity and Access to Justice,\b0 \i0 \ul0  61 Rutgers L. Rev. 1101 (2009); Christine Chambers Goodman, \b0 \i \ul0 Modest Proposal In Deference To Diversity,\b0 \i0 \ul0  23 Nat'l Black L.J. 1 (2010); Anjali Chavan, \b0 \i \ul0 The "Charles Morgan Letter" And Beyond: The Impact Of Diversity Initiatives On Big Law,\b0 \i0 \ul0  23 Geo. J. Legal Ethics 521 (2010); David A. Harvey, \b0 \i \ul0 A Preference for Equality: Seeking the Benefits of Diversity Outside the Educational Context,\b0 \i0 \ul0  21 BYU J. Pub. L. 55 (2007); W. Anthony Jenkins, \b0 \i \ul0 Diversity Matters: Here and Now,\b0 \i0 \ul0  90 Mich. B.J. 14 (2011); Kevin R. Johnson, \b0 \i \ul0 The Importance Of Student And Faculty Diversity In Law Schools: One Dean's Perspective,\b0 \i0 \ul0  96 Iowa L. Rev. 1549 (2011); Nancy Scherer, \b0 \i \ul0 Diversifying The Federal Bench: Is Universal Legitimacy For The U.S. Justice System Possible?,\b0 \i0 \ul0  105 Nw. U. L. Rev. 587 (2011); Carl Tobias, \b0 \i \ul0 Justifying Diversity in the \b0 \i0 \ul0 \b0 \i \ul0 Federal Judiciary,\b0 \i0 \ul0  106 Nw. U. L. Rev. Colloquy 283 (2012); Denelle J. Waynick, \b0 \i \ul0 Diversity -- Still a Business Imperative,\b0 \i0 \ul0  272 N.J. Law. 66 (Oct. 2011).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [**17]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \b0 \i \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 First,\b0 \i0 \ul0  providing racial minorities access to the legal profession brings to the bench their unique perspectives on the law. As Justice O'Connor said of former Justice Thurgood Marshall:
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri600 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri600 \sb0 \fi0 Although all of us come to the court with our own personal histories and experiences, Justice Marshall brought a special perspective . . . . Justice Marshall imparted not only his legal acumen but  \b \i0 \ul0 [*11]\b0 \i0 \ul0   also his life experiences, constantly pushing and prodding us to respond not only to the persuasiveness of legal argument but also to the power of moral truth. n17
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Likewise, Judge Leon Higginbotham, Jr. recognized that judicial diversity "creates a milieu in which the entire judicial system benefits from multi-faceted experiences with individuals who came from different backgrounds." n18 Similarly, Judge Harry Edwards of the D.C. Circuit has stated that "it is inevitable that judges' different professional and life experiences have some bearing on how they confront various problems that come before them." n19
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n17 Sandra Day O'Connor, \b0 \i \ul0 Thurgood Marshall: The Influence of a Raconteur,\b0 \i0 \ul0  44 Stan. L. Rev. 1217, 1217 (1992).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [**18]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n18 Leon Higginbotham, Jr., \b0 \i \ul0 Seeking Pluralism in Judicial Systems: The American Experience and the South African Challenge,\b0 \i0 \ul0  42 Duke L.J. 1028, 1037 (1993).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n19 Jonathan P. Kastellec, \b0 \i \ul0 Racial Diversity and Judicial Influence on Appellate Courts,\b0 \i0 \ul0  Princeton University, 1, 4 (Nov. 11, 2011), http://ssrn.com/abstract=1674052 (quoting Harry T. Edwards, \b0 \i \ul0 Race and the Judiciary,\b0 \i0 \ul0  20 Yale L. & Pol'y Rev. 325, 329 (2002)).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \b0 \i \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Second,\b0 \i0 \ul0  diversity in the legal profession is critical to ensuring the legitimacy of the judicial system because diversity fosters public confidence in the judicial system. As one scholar explained:
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri600 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri600 \sb0 \fi0 Diversity initiatives embody an effort to overcome bias, address discrimination, and pursue equality, all core values of the  \b \i0 \ul0 [*12]\b0 \i0 \ul0   legal profession and the rule of law. The United States occupies a special place among the nations of the world because of its commitment to equality, broad political participation, social mobility, and political representation of groups that lack political clout and/or ancestral power . . . . [W]ithout \b \i0 \ul0 [**19]\b0 \i0 \ul0   a diverse bench and bar, the rule of law is weakened as the people see and come to distrust their exclusion from mechanisms of justice. n20
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 An ABA report similarly noted that "[a] more diverse and representative legal profession will not only foster greater public confidence in the law, but even more fundamentally it will help to ensure fairness in the justice system." n21 For this reason, the ABA report called the diversification of the legal profession the greatest challenge for the legal profession in the twenty-first century. n22
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n20 Eli Wald, \b0 \i \ul0 A Primer on Diversity, Discrimination, and Equality in the Legal Profession or Who is Responsible for Pursuing Diversity and Why\b0 \i0 \ul0  24 Geo. J. Legal Ethics, 1079, 1101 (2011) (quoting Am. Bar Ass'n, \b0 \i \ul0 Presidential Diversity Initiative, Diversity in the Legal Profession: The Next Steps\b0 \i0 \ul0  (2010), \b0 \i \ul0 available at\b0 \i0 \ul0  http://www.americanbar.org/content/dam/aba/administrative/diversity/next_steps_2011.authcheckdam.pdf \b0 \i \ul0 ("Presidential Diversity Initiative")).\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n21 Kevin Gooch, \b0 \i \ul0 Embracing the Opportunities for Increasing Diversity Into the Legal Profession: Collaborating to Expand the Pipeline (Let's Get Real),\b0 \i0 \ul0  ABA Post-Conf. Rep. 1, 6 2006 http://www.americanbar.org/content/dam/aba/migrated/2011_build/diversity/pipelinepostreport.authcheckdam.pdf \b0 \i \ul0 ("Embracing the Opportunities").\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [**20]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n22 \b0 \i \ul0 Id.\b0 \i0 \ul0  at 6.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360  \b \i0 \ul0 [*13]\b0 \i0 \ul0   The benefits of diversity are particularly important in the judiciary because judges are among the most visible representatives of the legal system. As one scholar put it: "Diversity on the bench is intimately linked to the American promise to provide equal justice for all. Judges are the lynchpins of our system of justice." n23 That is, "[j]udges are not the exclusive providence of any one section of society . . . . [T]hey must provide justice for all." n24
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n23 Torres-Spelliscy et al., \b0 \i \ul0 supra,\b0 \i0 \ul0  at 1.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n24 \b0 \i \ul0 Id.\b0 \i0 \ul0  (quoting Jeffrey D. Jackson, \b0 \i \ul0 Beyond Quality: First Principles in Judicial Selection and Their Application to a Commission-Based Selection System,\b0 \i0 \ul0  34 Fordham Urb. L.J. 125, 145 (2007)).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \b0 \i \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Third,\b0 \i0 \ul0  diversity in the legal profession enhances the scope and quality of legal representation for many individuals who are racial minorities. Given this country's history \b \i0 \ul0 [**21]\b0 \i0 \ul0   of discrimination, it is crucial that a client have the ability to choose a lawyer with whom he or she feels comfortable. It is not simply that the availability of such lawyers affects the quality of representation that a minority client receives; it may determine whether that person seeks legal assistance at all. "Effective access to legal representation not only must exist in fact, it must also be perceived by the minority law consumer as existent so that recourse to law for the redress of grievance and the settlement of disputes becomes a realistic alternative to him." n25
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n25 Erwin N. Griswold, \b0 \i \ul0 Some Observations on the DeFunis Case,\b0 \i0 \ul0  75 Colum. L. Rev. 512, 517 (1975)).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360  \b \i0 \ul0 [*14]\b0 \i0 \ul0   \b0 \i \ul0 Fourth,\b0 \i0 \ul0  access to the legal profession creates access to the Nation's government because this Nation's political leaders often are drawn from the ranks of the legal profession. As the ABA has noted, "[a]dvancing diversity and inclusion in the . . . government is especially important. These fields not only administer,  \b \i0 \ul0 [**22]\b0 \i0 \ul0   but also represent democratic rule of law in our multicultural society. The absence of diversity and inclusion in . . . government can malign the legitimacy of not only lawyers, but also of the law itself." n26
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n26 \b0 \i \ul0 Presidential Diversity Initiative, supra,\b0 \i0 \ul0  at 33.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Indeed, of the forty-three men who have served as our Nation's president, twenty-five have been lawyers; of those, only one has been a racial minority. n27 Additionally, twenty-five of our Nation's current governors hold law degrees;' of those, only three are minorities. n28 Further, lawyers have long been the single largest occupational group in Congress. In the 112th Congress, 55 senators and 167 representatives are lawyers. n29 Despite the small proportion of people of color serving in the United States Congress, many of these lawmakers also have legal backgrounds. Indeed,  \b \i0 \ul0 [*15]\b0 \i0 \ul0   of the forty-three African-American members of Congress, nineteen are lawyers. n30 Both current Hispanic American members of the Senate and eight of the current twenty-five \b \i0 \ul0 [**23]\b0 \i0 \ul0   Hispanic Americans in the House of Representatives have law degrees. n31 And one of the two Asian Pacific-American Senators and three of the seven Asian Pacific-American representatives are attorneys. n32 These statistics show that access to this Nation's leadership is substantially influenced by access to the legal profession.
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n27 \b0 \i \ul0 Presidential Occupations,\b0 \i0 \ul0  http://www.infoplease.com/ipa/A0768854.html (last visited July 30, 2012).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n28 \b0 \i \ul0 Governors of the American States, Commonwealths and Territories,\b0 \i0 \ul0  National Governors Association 1 (2012), \b0 \i \ul0 available at\b0 \i0 \ul0  http://www.nga.org/files/live/sites/NGA/home/governors/current-governors/col2-content/list---governors-links/book-of-governors-biographies%40/BIOBOOK.PDF.
\par \fs20 \pard 
