\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Given the pervasive nature of the legal profession, ensuring diversity in the legal profession is a compelling governmental interest. As discussed below, race-conscious admissions programs at the collegiate level play a critical role in furthering this compelling interest.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*16]\b0 \i0 \ul0   \b \i0 \ul0 II. DIVERSITY IN THE LEGAL PROFESSION HAS NOT YET REACHED "CRITICAL MASS"\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Significant efforts have been made to achieve diversity in the legal profession. Private law firms have openly advocated for diversity in their ranks, and the judiciary has become more diverse with more racial minorities being appointed or elected to the federal and state judiciaries.  \b \i0 \ul0 [**25]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Nonetheless, due in part to this Nation's long history of discrimination, minorities still have a disproportionately low level of participation in the legal profession. The result of such low participation is that a critical mass of racial minorities in the legal profession has not been reached. Reaching this critical mass requires educational pipelines of the sort created by race-conscious admissions programs like the University of Texas's program. Absent such pipelines, minority participation in higher education would dramatically decline, which would deplete diversity in the legal profession. As a result, there remains a compelling governmental interest in achieving and maintaining critical mass in the legal profession, and race-conscious admissions programs are a proper means to achieve that goal.
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi0 A. Minorities Historically Have Been Excluded From Educational Opportunities And The Legal Profession\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 To understand the continuing need for programs that advance diversity, it is important to understand  \b \i0 \ul0 [*17]\b0 \i0 \ul0   the historical context of minority participation in this Nation's educational system. Discrimination against African Americans, Hispanic Americans, Asian Pacific Americans,  \b \i0 \ul0 [**26]\b0 \i0 \ul0   and Native Americans in education and other areas was pervasive in the formative years of this Nation. The lack of educational opportunity for minorities, including at the college level, meant that few minorities could move through the ranks into law schools and, ultimately, into the legal profession. n33
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n33 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  Floyd D. Weatherspoon, \b0 \i \ul0 The Status of African American Males in the Legal Profession: A Pipeline of Institutional Roadblocks and Barriers,\b0 \i0 \ul0  80 Miss L.J. 259, 280, 285, 290 (2010); \b0 \i \ul0 Embracing the Opportunities, supra.\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Historically, even long after the Civil War and emancipation, education of African Americans was permitted, but often only in segregated schools located in "old buildings, generally in filthy and degraded neighborhoods, dark, damp, small, and cheerless, safe neither for the morals nor the health of those who are compelled to go to them, if they go anywhere, and calculated to repel rather than to attract them." n34 Moreover, these schools received only 12% of public \b \i0 \ul0 [**27]\b0 \i0 \ul0   school funds despite being tasked with educating approximately one-third of the school-aged population. n35
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n34 August Meier & Elliot Rudwick, \b0 \i \ul0 From Plantation to Ghetto\b0 \i0 \ul0  109-14 (1966).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n35 Louis R. Harlan, \b0 \i \ul0 Separate and Unequal: Public School Campaigns and Racism in the Southern Seaboard States, 1901-1915\b0 \i0 \ul0  9-15 (1958).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 As a result of this discrimination, in 1940, only one-half of one percent of all attorneys in the United  \b \i0 \ul0 [*18]\b0 \i0 \ul0   States were African American, and discrimination against those few attorneys was rampant. n36 For example, most racial minorities were excluded from bar associations. Until 1943, the ABA excluded African Americans from membership. n37 And as late as 1950, a representative of the ABA testified in opposition to an attempt by African Americans to secure admission to the all-white University of North Carolina School of Law. n38 Indeed, \b0 \i \ul0 Amicus\b0 \i0 \ul0  the National Bar Association was founded in 1925 because African Americans were excluded from the ABA. n39 It was not until 1943 that \b \i0 \ul0 [**28]\b0 \i0 \ul0   the ABA allowed African Americans to join its ranks. n40
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n36 Derek Bok et al., \b0 \i \ul0 The Shape of the River: Long-Term Consequences of Considering Race in College and University Admissions\b0 \i0 \ul0  1 (1998).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n37 Am. Bar Ass'n, 68 \b0 \i \ul0 Annual Report of the American Bar Association\b0 \i0 \ul0  110 (1943).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n38 \b0 \i \ul0 See \b0 \i0 \ul0 \b0 \i \ul0 Epps v. Carmichael,\b0 \i0 \ul0  93 F. Supp. 327, 329 (M.D.N.C. 1950).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n39 \b0 \i \ul0 National Bar Association (1925.),\b0 \i0 \ul0  BlackPast.com, http://www.blackpast.org/?q=aah/national-bar-association-1925 (last visited Aug. 6, 2012).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n40 \b0 \i \ul0 Id.\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Like schools for African Americans, schools for Hispanic Americans "were usually segregated, overcrowded, and lacked adequately trained teachers." n41 The segregation of Hispanic Americans often was "justified" because of language differences. n42
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n41 Guadalupe San Miguel, Jr., "\b0 \i \ul0 Let All of Them Take Heed": Mexican Americans and the Campaign for Educational Equality in Texas, 1910-1981\b0 \i0 \ul0  11 (1987).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [**29]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n42 \b0 \i \ul0 See, e.g.,\b0 \i0 \ul0  Robert Alvarez, Jr., \b0 \i \ul0 Familia: Migration and Adaptation in Baja and Alta California, 1800-1975\b0 \i0 \ul0  154 (1987).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360  \b \i0 \ul0 [*19]\b0 \i0 \ul0   Similarly, Asian Pacific Americans faced racial discrimination in education. For example, in segregation era Mississippi, authorities treated Chinese Americans as "colored" and therefore prohibited them from attending all-Caucasian schools. n43 The Mississippi Supreme Court upheld the prohibition, reasoning that the word "colored" should be construed broadly to include children of "yellow" races. n44 Courts affirmed, applying the separate-but-equal doctrine of \b0 \i \ul0 Plessy v. Ferguson\b0 \i0 \ul0  n45 and other similar decisions. n46
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n43 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  Joyce Kuo, \b0 \i \ul0 Excluded, Segregated and Forgotten: A Historical View of the Discrimination of Chinese Americans,\b0 \i0 \ul0  5 Asian L.J. 181, 202 (1998); \b0 \i \ul0 see also\b0 \i0 \ul0  Sucheng Chan, \b0 \i \ul0 Asian Americans: An Interpretive History\b0 \i0 \ul0  58 (1991).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n44 \b0 \i \ul0 Rice v. Gong hum,\b0 \i0 \ul0  104 So. 105, 110 (1925).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n45 163 U.S. 537(1896).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [**30]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n46 \b0 \i \ul0 See, e.g., \b0 \i0 \ul0 \b0 \i \ul0 Gong hum u. Rice,\b0 \i0 \ul0  275 U.S. 78, 86-87 (1927).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Native Americans fared no better in education. The few schools established for their benefit sought to "assimilate," rather than educate. n47 This discrimination took place in spite of the United States's pledge in more than 100 treaties to provide educational services and facilities to Native Americans, in exchange for land. n48
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n47 L. Tsianina Lomawaima, \b0 \i \ul0 They Called It Prairie Light: The Story of the Chilocco Indian School\b0 \i0 \ul0  4 (1994).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n48 Donna Dehyle & Karen Swisher, \b0 \i \ul0 Research in American Indian and Alaska Native Education: From Assimilation to Self-Determination, in\b0 \i0 \ul0  22 Review of Research in Education 113, 114 (1997).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360  \b \i0 \ul0 [*20]\b0 \i0 \ul0   This Court first began to break down these discriminatory barriers in public legal education -- and thereby move toward recognizing diversity as a compelling interest -- in the 1940s. In \b0 \i \ul0 Sweatt v. Painter,\b0 \i0 \ul0   \b \i0 \ul0 [**31]\b0 \i0 \ul0   the Court ordered the admission of African Americans to the University of Texas Law School on the ground that the quality of the education available there was "superior" to that available at Texas's law school for African Americans. n49 Since \b0 \i \ul0 Sweatt,\b0 \i0 \ul0  the Court repeatedly has approved the constitutionality of state efforts that actively seek to ensure diversity in educational institutions for the benefit of all students -- minority and non-minority alike. n50 And these decisions by the Court have spurred other institutions to make efforts to address discrimination.
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n49 339 U.S. at 633-34.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n50 See, \b0 \i \ul0 e.g., \b0 \i0 \ul0 \b0 \i \ul0 Bakke,\b0 \i0 \ul0  438 U.S. at 315; \b0 \i \ul0 Grutter,\b0 \i0 \ul0  539 U.S. at 330.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Understanding the value of diversity in the legal profession, law schools have made efforts to diversify both their student bodies and their faculties. Like the University of Texas, many law schools have instituted race-conscious admissions programs. n51 Further, law schools have "sought to hire racial minorities \b \i0 \ul0 [**32]\b0 \i0 \ul0   . . . and [are] more committed to the success of their diverse faculty members both in terms of promotion to tenure . . . and in terms of appointments in leadership positions such as appointments as Associate Deans and Deans . . . ." n52
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n51 See, \b0 \i \ul0 e.g., \b0 \i0 \ul0 \b0 \i \ul0 Grutter,\b0 \i0 \ul0  539 U.S. 306.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n52 Wald, \b0 \i \ul0 supra,\b0 \i0 \ul0  at 1085-86.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360  \b \i0 \ul0 [*21]\b0 \i0 \ul0   Likewise, the ABA has made efforts to promote diversity in the legal profession. Since 1980, the ABA has required all law schools to demonstrate "a commitment to providing full opportunity for the study of law and entry into the profession of qualified members of groups, notably racial and ethnic minorities, which have been victims of discrimination in various forms." n53
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n53 Am. Bar Ass'n, \b0 \i \ul0 Standards for Approval of Law Schools\b0 \i0 \ul0  36-37, Standard 211 (2000).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Similarly, private law firms have made significant \b \i0 \ul0 [**33]\b0 \i0 \ul0   efforts to diversify their ranks. Most law firms have implemented recruiting policies that foster diversity in their associate and partner ranks. Indeed, one of the benchmarks employed to measure a law firm's success is the ability to hire a diverse group of attorneys. n54
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n54 \b0 \i \ul0 See Vault Law Firm Rankings 2013: The Best Law Firms For Diversity, available at\b0 \i0 \ul0  http://www.vault.com/wps/portal/usa/rankings/individual?rankingId1=36&rankingId2=36&rankings=2&regionId=0.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi0 B. Critical Mass Has Not Been Achieved In The Legal Profession\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Despite these efforts to diversify the legal profession, a critical mass of racial minorities still does not exist. Legal scholars have confirmed the continuing lack of a critical mass and continue to advocate for race-conscious admissions programs as a means to provide a stronger pipeline of minorities into the legal profession.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360  \b \i0 \ul0 [*22]\b0 \i0 \ul0   Stanford Law School professor Deborah Rhode, for example, recently wrote:
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri600 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri600 \sb0 \fi0 One irony of this nation's continuing struggle for diversity \b \i0 \ul0 [**34]\b0 \i0 \ul0   and gender equity in employment is that the profession leading the struggle has failed to set an example in its own workplaces. In principle, the bar is deeply committed to equal opportunity and social justice. In practice, it lags behind other occupations in leveling the playing field. n55
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Similarly, University of Louisville law professor Laura Rothstein noted the same trend, connecting it with the need to build a stronger pipeline for minorities:
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri600 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri600 \sb0 \fi0 A century of legalized racism, followed by decades of institutionalized racism, has resulted in the underrepresentation of minorities . . . in the legal profession . . . . Recognition of the need to open the door, give a chance, and provide opportunities that can make a difference highlight the value of institutional efforts to "shape the tributary" or "build the pipeline." n56
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n55 Deborah L. Rhode, \b0 \i \ul0 From Platitudes to Priorities: Diversity and Gender Equity in Law Firms,\b0 \i0 \ul0  24 Geo. J. Legal Ethics 1041, 1041 (2011).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n56 Laura Rothstein, \b0 \i \ul0 Shaping the Tributary, the Why, What and How of Pipeline Programs to Increase Diversity in Legal Education and the Legal Profession,\b0 \i0 \ul0  40 J.L. & Educ. 551, 552 (2011).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [**35]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360  \b \i0 \ul0 [*23]\b0 \i0 \ul0   Sarah Redfield, a law professor at the University of New Hampshire School of Law, likewise concluded:
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri600 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri600 \sb0 \fi0 For at least the past three decades, the legal profession has grappled with diversity issues, yet true diversity and inclusion eludes the practice of law . . . . Simply put, too few underrepresented minorities are progressing in school and moving successfully through the pipeline. Too few are graduating from high school and progressing to and succeeding in college. Too few are achieving LSAT scores and GPAs that meet the standards for admission to law school, all too few to contribute to a diverse profession. n57
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n57 Sarah Redfield, \b0 \i \ul0 The Educational Pipeline to Law School -- Too Broken and Too Narrow to Provide Diversity,\b0 \i0 \ul0  8 Pierce L. Rev. 347,353,358(2010).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The statistics regarding the representation of minorities in the legal profession bear out these scholars' conclusions. According to a January 2012 NALP bulletin, the number of Native-American associates in private \b \i0 \ul0 [**36]\b0 \i0 \ul0   practice nationwide is too low to be reported. NALP further reported that African Americans comprise only 4.29% of associates nationwide. n58 Even in geographic locations where African Americans represent a larger segment of the overall population, they are still underrepresented in  \b \i0 \ul0 [*24]\b0 \i0 \ul0   the associate ranks. For example, African Americans represent approximately 6% of the associates in the Detroit area (where 82.7% of the population is African American) and only slightly above 1% of the associates in San Diego, California (where 6.7% of the population is African American). n59
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n58 \b0 \i \ul0 NALP Bulletin, supra,\b0 \i0 \ul0  at Table 1.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n59 \b0 \i \ul0 Id.; State & County Quick Facts -- Detroit (city), Michigan,\b0 \i0 \ul0  United States Census Bureau, http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/26/2622000.html (last revised June 6, 2012); \b0 \i \ul0 State & County Quick Facts -- San Diego (city), California,\b0 \i0 \ul0  United States Census Bureau, http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/06/0666000.html (last revised June 6, 2012).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Hispanic Americans have similarly \b \i0 \ul0 [**37]\b0 \i0 \ul0   low participation in the associate ranks, representing only 3.83% of associates nationwide and close to 0% in certain markets. n60 For example, Hispanic Americans represent less than 2% of the associate ranks in fifteen of the forty-four markets surveyed by NALP. n61 This includes legal markets where there is a relatively high Hispanic population, such as Las Vegas, Nevada (where Hispanic Americans make up 31.5% of the population, but only 1.18% of associates) and San Diego, California (where Hispanic Americans constitute 28.8% of the population, but only 3.2% of associates). n62
\par \pard 
