\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 III. ELIMINATING RACE-CONSCIOUS COLLEGE ADMISSIONS WOULD SIGNIFICANTLY REDUCE DIVERSITY IN THE LEGAL PROFESSION\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 To ensure the creation and maintenance of a critical mass of racial minorities in the legal profession, a pipeline must be maintained to allow qualified minorities the opportunity to earn admission to college and then law school and ultimately to enter the legal profession. When states have eliminated race-conscious admissions programs entirely,  \b \i0 \ul0 [**42]\b0 \i0 \ul0   the results have been disastrous. Without race-conscious admissions programs, racial minorities' college enrollment plummeted, and, by extension, minority law  \b \i0 \ul0 [*28]\b0 \i0 \ul0   school admissions fell dramatically. This resulted in a narrowing of the pipeline into the legal profession, which significantly reduced the number of racial minorities who became lawyers.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In July of 1995, the Regents of the University of California adopted Resolution SP-1, which eliminated "race, religion, sex, color, ethnicity, or national origin as criteria for admission" to the university system. n77 In November of 1996, California voters approved Proposition 209, which amended California's state constitution to prohibit the consideration of race, religion, sex, color, ethnicity, or national origin in admissions. n78
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n77 University of California -- Office of the President, \b0 \i \ul0 Undergraduate Access to the University of California After the Elimination of Race-Conscious Policies\b0 \i0 \ul0  7 (March 2003). Resolution SP-1 was rescinded in May 2001. \b0 \i \ul0 Id.\b0 \i0 \ul0  at 7 n.7.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n78 \b0 \i \ul0 Id.\b0 \i0 \ul0  at 7.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [**43]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The impact of these policies was immediate. Between 1995, when Resolution SP-1 was adopted, and 1998, when both Resolution SP-1 and Proposition 209 took effect, the number of in-state African-American, Hispanic-American, and Native-American students admitted to the University of California, Berkeley dropped 58%. n79 When Proposition 209 officially took effect for the entering class of Fall 1998, the admission rates of minorities on all California campuses declined, including by as much as 50% at the University of  \b \i0 \ul0 [*29]\b0 \i0 \ul0   California, Berkeley and the University of California, Los Angeles. n80
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n79 Erica Perez, \b0 \i \ul0 Despite Diversity Efforts, UC Minority Enrollment Down Since Prop. 209,\b0 \i0 \ul0  California Watch 1, (Feb. 24, 2012) http://californiawatch.org/dailyreport/despite-diversity-efforts-uc-minority-enrollment-down-prop-209-15031.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n80 \b0 \i \ul0 Id.\b0 \i0 \ul0  at 2.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Admissions numbers continue to drop steadily. For example, just between 2002 and 2003, admissions rates fell 15% for African Americans, 3% for Hispanic Americans,  \b \i0 \ul0 [**44]\b0 \i0 \ul0   9.2% for Native Americans, and 2% for Asian Pacific Americans. n81
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n81 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  Carl G. Cooper, \b0 \i \ul0 Increasing Pipeline Opportunities in the Legal Profession for Minorities,\b0 \i0 \ul0  The Metropolitan Corporate Counsel (Vol. 15, No. 3, March 2007).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 To this day, the percentage of minorities admitted to and enrolled in California law schools remains materially lower than the percentage admitted and enrolled before the implementation of Proposition 209. n82 This decrease in minority enrollment has had a  \b \i0 \ul0 [*30]\b0 \i0 \ul0   corresponding effect on the legal profession in California, with fewer attorneys of color entering the ranks. In fact, one study determined that the elimination of race as a factor in admissions would result in at least a 50% net loss of new minority attorneys. n83
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n82 Perez, \b0 \i \ul0 supra,\b0 \i0 \ul0  at 1. This decrease in enrollment applies to Asian Pacific Americans, as well as African Americans, Hispanic Americans, and Native Americans. That Asian Pacific Americans have seen a decrease in admissions following the passage of Proposition 209 refutes the "model minority" myth, which contends that Asian Pacific Americans stand to gain the most from the demise of race as a factor in college and law school admissions. \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  Stephen Thernstrom & Abigail Thernstrom, \b0 \i \ul0 Reflections on the Shape of the River,\b0 \i0 \ul0  46 UCLA L. Rev. 1583, 1629 (1999) (asserting that Asian Pacific Americans derive the greatest benefit when race-conscious admissions policies are eliminated); \b0 \i \ul0 see also\b0 \i0 \ul0  Frank Wu, \b0 \i \ul0 Yellow: Race in America Beyond Black and White\b0 \i0 \ul0  49, 74-77 (2001) (describing the "model minority" myth generally). In fact, only one racial group showed marked increases in enrollment following the passage of Proposition 209; Caucasian Americans accounted for 59.8% of law school enrollment during the three years before Proposition 209; they made up 71.7% of law school students in California after the ban. \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  William C. Kidder, \b0 \i \ul0 Situating Asian Pacific Americans in the Law School Affirmative Action Debate: Empirical Facts About Thernstrom's Rhetorical Acts,\b0 \i0 \ul0  7 Asian L.J. 29, 43-45 (2000).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [**45]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n83 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  Jesse Rothstein & Albert H. Yoon, The National Bureau of Economic Research, \b0 \i \ul0 Affirmative Action in Law School Admissions: What Do Racial Preferences Do?\b0 \i0 \ul0  4 (2008).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 California's experience shows that eliminating race-conscious admissions programs for racial minorities has immediate and significant effects, reducing the number of people of color entering the legal profession. Without a robust pipeline, fewer racial minority candidates obtain access to college and, in turn, law school and the legal profession. This results in a lack of diversity in the legal profession. Thus, given the continuing need to foster diversity, there continues to be a compelling governmental interest in collegiate diversity as a means to further a pipeline to achieve diversity in the legal profession.
\par \pard 
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 IV. CONCLUSION\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Diversity is of paramount importance in law schools because they "represent the training ground for a large number of the Nation's leaders" and "legal learning and practice . . . cannot be effective in isolation from the individuals and institutions with  \b \i0 \ul0 [*31]\b0 \i0 \ul0   which the law interacts.  \b \i0 \ul0 [**46]\b0 \i0 \ul0   " n84 Moreover, diversity strengthens the legal system as a whole: it ensures that numerous perspectives will be heard; it ensures that the legal system has legitimacy in the eyes of society; it increases access to legal representation for all; and it prepares our Nation's leaders. Diversity in the legal profession can only be fed by the flow of talented and qualified students through college and law school; and this pipeline is maintained, in part, by race-conscious college and law school admissions. Accordingly, race-conscious admissions programs remain a necessary and compelling governmental interest.
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n84 \b0 \i \ul0 Grutter,\b0 \i0 \ul0  539 U.S. at 332 (citing \b0 \i \ul0 Sweatt,\b0 \i0 \ul0  339 U.S. at 634).
\par \fs20 \b0 \i \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Amici\b0 \i0 \ul0  therefore respectfully join Respondents in requesting this Court uphold the University of Texas's program.
